name: Aussie Style Brunching... in West London

text.text: Aussie Style Brunching... in West London

In case you're wondering what exactly characterises an Aussie brunch, we checked: turns out it's a mixture of Asian influences (hiya kimchi), more savoury than sweet, lots of whole grains, plenty of veggies, real coffee, smooth lattes, ferments and juices galore. It's the kind of fuel that isn't exactly fat free, but has a more wholesome feel than our usual bowl of cardboard flakes and instant coffee. 

It's the kind of food West Londoners refuel on post workout, so (even if you've just rolled out of bed) squeeze into your yoga gear, get those muscles out and head to one of the below, 'cause in these ends, Aussie brunch is a big ol' business.

tip.text: Dropping in here is kind of like visiting the rustic pantry of a middle-class mum's house, where the cupboards are always stocked and she's cool with you spending the entire afternoon in there because you've got nowhere to be. It's all-day dining, but brunch, and its egg variations, is certainly centre stage: they feature in everything from the humble scrambled egg on toast to super comforting dishes like the sweet potato rosti with poached egg, goat's cheese, honey, kale and dill yoghurt. This place is built for comfort and fuelling: perfect for a post-yoga bite, if you do yoga (and if you live in these ends, you do).

tip.text:
Picture the scene: its late and the stars are out... an Aussie babe and a Turkish hunk get together to create an Aussie-Turkish love child and they call it Brew Cafe. And then they have a few more children in West London and suddenly Brew Cafe has earned itself a bit of a reputation for decent, if a touch expensive, all-day dining.

In a relaxed and informal setting their huge menu takes care of all the essential eating requirements, though we'd tip coming in for their decent Mediterranean-inspired breakfasts or brunch. They bake their own bread, they make their own cakes, they wood-fire their own pizzas - it's a serious operation, though the prices mean it's not an everyday kinda joint.

text.text: Picture the scene, its late and the stars are out... an Aussie babe and a Turkish hunk get together to create an Aussie-Turkish love child and they call it Brew Cafe. Pop down to Clapham South for some bonzer breakfast - if you're hanging we rate going in for the Brew Melt (ham, gruyere, vine tomato, poached eggs and pesto served on toasted pide). It's not a big place, though, so it tends to get a bit rammo on the weekends.

tip.text: Theres no use denying it, Australians do brunch best, and Aussie cafe Brickwood is proof (it has three locations in the South West London area). Commence lazy brunching with a smooth flat white and follow up with something like the wild mushroom and poached egg on sourdough with basil pesto, tarragon and balsamic dressing - phwoar, phwoar and more phwoar. Also, on a sunny day you know you want a piece of that patio out back.

tip.text:
Exposed brick walls, worn wooden tables, a whole lotta sourdough... you can smell the Antipodean influence as soon as you walk in. Though the owner's Welsh (who opened the cafe after a stint in AUS, mind you), the staff is from down undah and the avo is smashed - which makes Mud an Aussie brunch spot in our books.

Expect big-name classics and more obscure brunch bangers on their ever-changing menu. The corn fritter stack - a firm fan fave - is a menu mainstay, piled high with avo, chilli jam, and an egg. Though the portions are hearty, the fresh ingredients make you feel like you're doing your body a solid. Queues rack up at the weekends, so get there early, or do the smart thing and grab some bed-bound takeaway.

tip.text:
Those down-under folk really know their way around an espresso machine. Farm Girl is a perfect example of what an Aussie can do when combining food, drink, and art to make a seriously chilled hang-out spot.

An ode to Melbourne and an ode to coconuts, this sunny Notting Hill haven is fast becoming a West London fave. The walls are decorated with awesome shiny blue tiles, the courtyard is a cosy sun trap and the food is holistic and healthy. Dont let that last bit put you off, as the food is delicious (and nutritious) - try superfood smoothies, white Devon crab cakes and the millet porridge topped with all kinds of seeds, omega mix, and bee pollen(?!). Tired of your regular old cappuccino? Why not go for something more adventurous like a liquid gold latte with turmeric, cinnamon, astralagus, and honey.

tip.text:
Bill Granger is bringing Aussie-style dining to London with generous, fresh-from-the-beach dishes. For those of you who dont know (which we guess might be a few), Bill Granger is an Australian chef with quite a bit of media presence- known for his easy manner and general cheerfulness that is the embodiment of Australian dining. Hes now taken the plunge across the pond, and us pommies are lappin it up.

Chelsea money has impregnated the Granger style a touch, with more dark wood and green velvet bench seating, but that fresh colourful food is reliably fab. We'll have the non alcoholic jax seedlip ginger spritz please, we've a very important meeting this afternoon.

tip.text:
An old post office nestled in the heart of the leafy Kew Village, this place would be easily missed for all the other airy, artisanal boutiques around. But dip inside and youll find a sunny ode to Melbourne brasserie culture, with comfy decor, cracking coffee and delicious grub.

The food is a loose collection of world dishes, with a focus on fresh, seasonal ingredients, all served with flavour and flare for days. With everything from tonkatsu pork with coconut and lime rice to crispy barramundi with courgette, mint and pistachio, this place is bringing the quantity and quality in equal measure. Theyre open from morn' till night, so come by anytime, just be sure to book in advance as its very popular with the locals.
